{
"proposed_text": "STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE: SOP-101\nTITLE: ELECTRONIC RECORDS AND SYSTEM ACCESS CONTROL\nVERSION: 2.0\nEFFECTIVE DATE: [Insert Date]\nREVIEW CYCLE: Triennial\n\n1.0 PURPOSE\nThis procedure establishes the administrative, technical, and physical controls to ensure system security, access control, electronic record integrity, and secure data transmission in compliance with FDA 21 CFR Part 11 and the binding regulatory update Docket No. FDA-2026-N-8841. It mandates password aging, session timeout, encryption, audit trail generation, and dual-authorization approvals for all electronic records and system modifications.\n\n2.0 SCOPE\nThis SOP applies to all computer systems, network domains, software tools, and transmission channels that generate, maintain, modify, retrieve, transmit, or store quality records, including but not limited to laboratory information management systems (LIMS), enterprise resource planning (ERP) systems, manufacturing telemetry nodes, and remote clinical control modules.\n\n3.0 SYSTEM ACCESS CONTROLS\n3.1 Password Complexity and Aging:\n- User passwords must be a minimum of 8 characters, containing at least one uppercase letter, one lowercase letter, one numeric digit, and one special character.\n- Passwords must be changed every 90 days. The system shall enforce password history to prevent reuse of the previous 5 passwords.\n- New accounts must change the temporary password upon first login.\n\n3.2 Session Timeout:\n- Computer terminals and software applications must automatically log out a user or lock the display terminal after 15 minutes of continuous keyboard or mouse inactivity. This timeout is not overridable by end users.\n\n3.3 Account Lockout:\n- If a user enters an incorrect password three (3) consecutive times, the system will automatically lock the user account for 30 minutes. Account unlock requests must be approved by the IT System Administrator and documented in the incident log.\n\n3.4 User Privileges:\n- All write, modification, and approval privileges are strictly restricted according to user roles. Authority checks must be performed before any transaction is executed. Role assignments are reviewed quarterly by the Quality Assurance department.\n\n4.0 ENCRYPTION OF RECORDS IN TRANSMISSION\n4.1 All electronic records transmitted over internal or external networks must be encrypted using Transport Layer Security (TLS) version 1.3 or higher.\n4.2 System administrators shall configure all validated applications to enforce TLS 1.3 for data in transit. Any legacy system incapable of TLS 1.3 must be isolated behind a compensating control (e.g., VPN with equivalent encryption) and documented in the system risk assessment.\n\n5.0 AUDIT TRAIL REQUIREMENTS\n5.1 All systems that create, modify, or delete electronic records shall generate a computer-generated, time-stamped audit trail that records the date, time (with time zone), and author (user ID) of each action.\n5.2 Audit trails must be secure, independently verifiable, and retained for the same period as the associated electronic records. They shall not be editable by any user, including system administrators.\n5.3 Operational supervisors must perform an exhaustive, independent quality assurance verification and cryptographic sign-off of all active system transaction audit trails at least weekly, as per SOP-VAL-312.\n\n6.0 DUAL-AUTHORIZATION APPROVALS\n6.1 All modifications to standard operating procedures (SOPs) and all document releases (e.g., batch records, validation reports) require strict dual-authorization approval.\n6.2 The dual-authorization workflow shall consist of two distinct authorized individuals: one to prepare/author the change and a second to review and approve. Both approvals must be executed via electronic signatures that comply with SOP-102.\n6.3 The system shall prevent a single individual from both authoring and approving the same document. An audit trail entry must capture both approval events.\n\n7.0 INCIDENT RESPONSE AND REPORTING\n7.1 In the event of a verified cyber security anomaly, unauthorized access, or network compromise impacting active production or patient records, the holding corporate entity must submit a comprehensive digital incident notification file to the FDA Emergency Cyber-Response Dashboard within four (4) clock hours of initial engineering identification, as per FDA-2026-N-8841.\n\n8.0 COMPLIANCE AND TRAINING\n8.1 All personnel with access to systems covered by this SOP must complete annual training on electronic record integrity and security awareness.\n8.2 Non-compliance with this SOP may result in disciplinary action and shall be reported to the Quality Assurance department.\n\n9.0 REFERENCES\n- 21 CFR Part 11\n- FDA Docket No. FDA-2026-N-8841\n- SOP-102: Electronic Signatures and Signing Authority\n- SOP-VAL-312: System Audit Trails and Data Integrity\n- SOP-IT-101: Electronic Records and System Access Control (superseded)\n\n10.0 REVISION HISTORY\nVersion 1.0: Initial release.\nVersion 2.0: Updated to incorporate password aging, 15-minute session timeout, TLS 1.3 encryption, audit trail mandates, dual-authorization approvals, and incident reporting per FDA-2026-N-8841.",
