"rationale": "The original SOP-101 lacked several critical controls mandated by the updated regulation. The following changes were made to achieve full compliance:\n\n1. **Password Aging (Section 3.1)**: Added 90-day expiration, history restriction, and first-login change to strengthen authentication and prevent credential reuse, aligning with 21 CFR Part 11.10(d) (limiting system access to authorized individuals) and FDA-2026-N-8841.\n\n2. **Session Timeout Reduction (Section 3.2)**: Reduced idle timeout from 30 minutes to 15 minutes to minimize unauthorized access risk, as required by the regulation update and consistent with 21 CFR Part 11.10(d).\n\n3. **Encryption in Transmission (Section 4)**: Introduced mandatory TLS 1.3 encryption for all data in transit to protect record integrity and confidentiality, addressing the regulation’s explicit requirement and supporting 21 CFR Part 11.10(c) (protection of records).\n\n4. **Audit Trail (Section 5)**: Added a comprehensive audit trail requirement for all record actions, including time-stamped, computer-generated logs that are non-editable and independently verified. This directly satisfies 21 CFR Part 11.10(e) and the regulation’s audit trail mandate.\n\n5. **Dual-Authorization Approvals (Section 6)**: Implemented a strict two-person approval workflow for SOP modifications and document releases, ensuring no single individual can unilaterally alter records. This meets the regulation’s dual-authorization requirement and aligns with 21 CFR Part 11.10(j) (authority checks) and 11.200(a) (electronic signature components).\n\n6. **Incident Reporting (Section 7)**: Added a 4-hour FDA notification obligation for cyber incidents, as per FDA-2026-N-8841, to ensure transparency and rapid response.\n\nAll revisions are grounded in the provided regulatory context and internal QMS documents (SOP-IT-101, SOP-VAL-312) to maintain consistency with existing corporate policies."
