{
"proposed_text": "STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE: SOP-102\nTITLE: ELECTRONIC SIGNATURES AND SIGNING AUTHORITY\nVERSION: 2.0\nEFFECTIVE DATE: [Insert Date]\nREVIEW CYCLE: Triennial\n\n1.0 PURPOSE\nThis procedure establishes the administrative, technical, and procedural controls for electronic signatures to ensure they are the legally binding equivalent of handwritten signatures, and to maintain the trustworthiness, reliability, and integrity of electronic records in compliance with FDA-2026-N-8841 and 21 CFR Part 11.\n\n2.0 SCOPE\nThis SOP applies to all electronic signatures executed on GxP documents, including standard operating procedures, validation plans, clinical reports, batch release records, electronic batch records (eBR), design history files (DHF), and any other electronic records within the electronic quality management system (eQMS). It also governs the system-level controls for access, encryption, audit trails, and dual-authorization approvals that support the electronic signature process.\n\n3.0 DEFINITIONS\n3.1 Electronic Signature: A computer data compilation of any symbol or series of symbols executed, adopted, or authorized by an individual to be the legally binding equivalent of the individual's handwritten signature.\n3.2 Dual-Component Authentication: The use of two distinct identification components (e.g., user ID and password, or biometric plus password) to verify the identity of the signer.\n3.3 Audit Trail: A secure, computer-generated, time-stamped electronic record that allows for reconstruction of the course of events relating to the creation, modification, or deletion of an electronic record.\n3.4 Dual-Authorization: A process requiring the independent approval of two authorized individuals before an action (e.g., SOP modification, document release) is finalized.\n\n4.0 SYSTEM ACCESS CONTROLS\n4.1 Password Aging: User passwords shall expire every 90 days. The system shall enforce password history to prevent reuse of the previous 5 passwords.\n4.2 Account Lockout: After three (3) consecutive failed login attempts, the user account shall be automatically locked for a minimum of 30 minutes. Unlock shall require intervention by the System Administrator following identity verification.\n4.3 Session Timeout: All active sessions shall be automatically terminated after 15 minutes of user inactivity (no keyboard or mouse input). The user must re-authenticate to resume the session.\n4.4 Password Complexity: Passwords must be a minimum of 8 characters, containing at least one uppercase letter, one lowercase letter, one numeric digit, and one special character.\n\n5.0 ENCRYPTION OF ELECTRONIC RECORDS\n5.1 All electronic records containing signatures, and any data transmitted between system components or over networks, shall be encrypted using Transport Layer Security (TLS) version 1.3 or higher.\n5.2 Encryption keys shall be managed in accordance with the company's Information Security Policy and shall be rotated annually.\n\n6.0 AUDIT TRAIL REQUIREMENTS\n6.1 The system shall generate a secure, computer-generated, time-stamped audit trail for all actions that create, modify, or delete electronic records. The audit trail shall record:\n    a) The date and time (UTC) of the action.\n    b) The unique user ID of the individual performing the action.\n    c) The nature of the action (create, modify, delete).\n    d) The previous and new values for any modified data fields.\n6.2 Audit trails shall be retained for the same period as the associated electronic records and shall be available for FDA inspection and internal review.\n6.3 Audit trails shall be protected from unauthorized modification or deletion.\n\n7.0 DUAL-AUTHORIZATION APPROVALS\n7.1 Any modification to a standard operating procedure (SOP) or release of a GxP document (e.g., batch record, validation report) shall require dual-authorization. This means two independent, authorized individuals must each apply their electronic signature to approve the change or release.\n7.2 The system shall enforce that the two approvers are distinct and have the appropriate role-based permissions. The first approver cannot be the same as the author or the second approver.\n7.3 The dual-authorization event shall be captured in the audit trail with both signatures and timestamps.\n\n8.0 ELECTRONIC SIGNATURE REQUIREMENTS\n8.1 Dual-Component Authentication: The execution of an electronic signature shall require the input of two distinct identification components: a unique user ID and password, or a biometric identifier combined with password authentication. Signatures not executed during a single continuous logged session must necessitate re-entry of both components.\n8.2 Signature Manifestation: Every electronically signed document must visually display the following three signature components:\n    a) The printed name of the signer.\n    b) The date and time stamp (UTC) when the signature was executed.\n    c) The meaning associated with the signature (e.g., review, approval, authorship, or responsibility).\n8.3 Non-Repudiation: Electronic signatures shall be unique to one individual and shall not be copied, reassigned, or transferred. No two individuals shall share signing credentials. The system shall employ cryptographic or logical locks to bind the signature to the record, such that any subsequent modification to the record invalidates the signature.\n8.4 Electronic Signature Affirmation: Prior to granting electronic signing privileges, the Quality Assurance organization shall obtain a signed, written statement from the employee certifying that their electronic signature is the legally binding equivalent of their handwritten signature. This physical document shall be archived indefinitely.\n\n9.0 TRAINING\nAll personnel with electronic signing authority shall complete training on this SOP and the associated system functionality. Training records shall be documented and maintained.\n\n10.0 REFERENCES\n- 21 CFR Part 11\n- FDA-2026-N-8841\n- SOP-101: Electronic Records and System Access Control\n- SOP-VAL-312: System Audit Trails and Data Integrity\n- SOP-IT-103: Incident Management Protocol\n\n11.0 REVISION HISTORY\nVersion 1.0: Initial release.\nVersion 2.0: Comprehensive revision to incorporate FDA-2026-N-8841 requirements including password aging, session timeout, encryption, audit trail, and dual-authorization approvals.",
"citations": [
"21 CFR Part 11.10(b)",
"21 CFR Part 11.10(d)",
"21 CFR Part 11.10(e)",
"21 CFR Part 11.200(a)",
"21 CFR Part 11.300",
"FDA-2026-N-8841"
],
"rationale": "The original SOP-102 only addressed basic electronic signature components (dual-factor, manifestation, non-repudiation) and lacked critical system-level controls mandated by the updated FDA regulation. The revision integrates: (1) Password aging and account lockout after 3 failed attempts (21 CFR Part 11.300, FDA-2026-N-8841) to prevent unauthorized access; (2) Session timeout reduced to 15 minutes (21 CFR Part 11.10(b)) to mitigate risk of unattended sessions; (3) Encryption with TLS 1.3 (21 CFR Part 11.10(d)) to protect data in transit; (4) Computer-generated, time-stamped audit trails (21 CFR Part 11.10(e)) to ensure data integrity and traceability; (5) Dual-authorization for SOP modifications and document releases (FDA-2026-N-8841) to enforce independent review. Additionally, the signature manifestation now requires UTC timestamps and cryptographic binding to the record, and an affirmation statement is required, aligning with 21 CFR Part 11.200(a) and internal QMS standards. These changes ensure the SOP is fully compliant with the new regulation and industry best practices."
}
