"proposed_text": "STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE: SOP-103\nTITLE: SYSTEM AUDIT TRAILS AND DATA INTEGRITY\nVERSION: 2\n\n1.0 PURPOSE\nThis procedure establishes the administrative, technical, and procedural controls to ensure the trustworthiness, reliability, and integrity of electronic records and their associated audit trails. It mandates system-enforced mechanisms for access control, session security, encryption, audit trail generation, and document approval workflows in compliance with FDA 21 CFR Part 11 and FDA-2026-N-8841.\n\n2.0 SCOPE\nThis SOP applies to all computer systems, applications, and network services that create, modify, delete, or transmit GxP electronic records. It covers user authentication, session management, data-in-transit protection, computer-generated audit trails, and the dual-authorization process for SOP modifications and document releases.\n\n3.0 ACCESS CONTROL AND AUTHENTICATION\n3.1 Password Complexity and Aging: User passwords must be a minimum of 8 characters, containing at least one uppercase letter, one lowercase letter, one numeric digit, and one special character. Passwords shall expire every 90 days, and password history of the last 5 passwords shall be enforced to prevent reuse. (21 CFR Part 11.300(a))\n3.2 Account Lockout: After three (3) consecutive failed login attempts, the system shall automatically lock the user account for a minimum of 30 minutes. Account unlock shall require intervention by a system administrator or an automated reset after the lockout period. (21 CFR Part 11.300(b))\n3.3 Session Timeout: All user sessions shall be automatically terminated after 15 minutes of inactivity. The system must lock the display or log out the user, requiring re-authentication to resume activity. (21 CFR Part 11.300(c))\n\n4.0 DATA TRANSMISSION SECURITY\n4.1 Encryption: All electronic records transmitted over any network (internal or external) must be encrypted using Transport Layer Security (TLS) version 1.3 or higher. Unencrypted transmission of GxP records is prohibited. (21 CFR Part 11.30)\n\n5.0 AUDIT TRAIL MANAGEMENT\n5.1 Automatic Generation: Computer-generated, time-stamped audit trails shall be automatically produced by the system and capture the date, time (synchronized to a trusted time source), user identity, and specific action (create, modify, delete) for all electronic record transactions. (21 CFR Part 11.10(e))\n5.2 Immutability: Audit trail records must be secured against modification, editing, or deletion by any user, including system administrators and database developers. The system architecture shall preclude any facility to pause, disable, or rewrite logged metadata. (21 CFR Part 11.10(e); FDA-2026-N-8841 Section 3.1)\n5.3 Regular Review: Operational supervisors or delegated Quality Assurance representatives shall perform an exhaustive, independent review of all active system transaction audit trails at a frequency not to exceed 30 calendar days. Evidence of review, including any anomalies and corrective actions, must be documented via a cryptographically signed electronic audit attestation log. (21 CFR Part 11.10(e); FDA-2026-N-8841 Section 3.2)\n5.4 Retention: Audit trails shall be retained for a period no less than the retention requirements of the electronic records they document, and in no case less than 5 years, unless otherwise specified by applicable regulations. (21 CFR Part 11.10(e))\n\n6.0 DOCUMENT CONTROL AND DUAL-AUTHORIZATION\n6.1 SOP Modifications and Document Releases: Any modification to this SOP or any GxP document release shall require strict dual-authorization. Two authorized individuals, one from the originating department and one from Quality Assurance, must electronically sign and approve the change before it becomes effective. The system shall record both signatures in the audit trail. (21 CFR Part 11.10(a); FDA-2026-N-8841 Section 6.5)\n\n7.0 INCIDENT RESPONSE\n7.1 In the event of a verified cybersecurity anomaly, unauthorized access, or data compromise impacting electronic records, the incident shall be reported to the FDA Emergency Cyber-Response Dashboard within 4 hours of identification, as per FDA-2026-N-8841 Section 4.2.\n\n8.0 TRAINING\nAll personnel with access to systems covered by this SOP shall receive training on these procedures upon initial assignment and annually thereafter. Training records shall be maintained.\n\n9.0 REVISION HISTORY\nVersion 2: [Date] – Comprehensive revision to incorporate access controls, encryption, dual-authorization, and updated audit trail requirements per FDA-2026-N-8841 and 21 CFR Part 11.",
"original_text": "STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE: SOP-103\nTITLE: SYSTEM AUDIT TRAILS AND DATA INTEGRITY\nVERSION: 1\n\n1.0 PURPOSE\nDefines the management, protection, and review of system audit trails to prevent unauthorized modifications and ensure record traceability.\n\n2.0 SCOPE\nApplies to all computer-generated, time-stamped audit trails recording the date, time, user identity, and specific actions of system transactions.\n\n3.0 AUDIT TRAIL MANAGEMENT\n3.1 Automatic Generation: Audit trails must be automatically generated by the system and capture all record creation, modification, and deletion events.\n3.2 Immutability: Audit trails must be secured against modifications, edits, or deletion by any user, including system administrators and database developers.\n3.3 Regular Review: System audit trails must be reviewed by the Quality Assurance (QA) Department at least once every 30 days. Evidence of audit trail review must be documented.\n3.4 Retention: Audit trails must be retained for a duration no less than the retention requirements of the electronic records they document.",
