{
"proposed_text": "STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE: SOP-110\nTITLE: BATCH RECORD REVIEW AND QUALITY RELEASE\nVERSION: 2\nEFFECTIVE DATE: [Insert Date]\nREVIEW CYCLE: Triennial\n\n1.0 PURPOSE\nThis procedure defines the systematic review, approval, and release process for Batch Manufacturing Records (BMR) and associated analytical testing records. It ensures that all batches conform to predetermined specifications and that electronic records and signatures used in the release process are trustworthy, reliable, and equivalent to paper records, in compliance with 21 CFR Part 11 and FDA Docket No. FDA-2026-N-8841.\n\n2.0 SCOPE\nThis SOP applies to all commercial batches of drug substances and drug products manufactured by BioPharma Corp. It covers all electronic systems used to create, modify, review, approve, and store batch records, including electronic batch records (eBR), laboratory information management systems (LIMS), and quality management software (eQMS).\n\n3.0 DEFINITIONS\n3.1 Electronic Record: Any combination of text, graphics, data, audio, pictorial, or other information representation created, modified, maintained, archived, retrieved, or distributed by a computer system.\n3.2 Electronic Signature: A computer data compilation of any symbol or series of symbols executed, adopted, or authorized by an individual to be the legally binding equivalent of the individual's handwritten signature.\n3.3 Audit Trail: A secure, computer-generated, time-stamped electronic record that allows reconstruction of the course of events relating to the creation, modification, or deletion of an electronic record.\n3.4 Dual-Authorization: A process requiring the independent approval of two authorized individuals before a document or record is considered released.\n\n4.0 SYSTEM ACCESS AND SECURITY CONTROLS\nAll computer systems used in the batch record review and release process must enforce the following minimum controls, as detailed in SOP-IT-101 (Electronic Records and System Access Control):\n4.1 Password Complexity and Aging: User passwords must be at least eight (8) characters, containing characters from three of the following four categories: uppercase letters, lowercase letters, numeric digits, and special characters. Passwords must be changed every 90 days, and the system must prevent reuse of the previous five (5) passwords.\n4.2 Account Lockout: After three (3) consecutive failed login attempts, the user account shall be automatically locked for a minimum of 30 minutes. Unlock requires intervention by a system administrator following identity verification.\n4.3 Session Timeout: All user sessions shall be automatically terminated after 15 minutes of continuous keyboard or mouse inactivity. Re-authentication is required to resume the session.\n4.4 Encryption: All electronic records transmitted between systems or over networks must be encrypted using Transport Layer Security (TLS) version 1.3 or higher.\n\n5.0 AUDIT TRAIL REQUIREMENTS\n5.1 Any system that creates, modifies, or deletes electronic batch records or associated release documentation must generate a secure, computer-generated, time-stamped audit trail.\n5.2 The audit trail shall record, at a minimum: the date and time of the action, the user identification of the individual performing the action, and a description of the action (e.g., record creation, data modification, approval, deletion).\n5.3 Audit trail records must be retained for the same period as the associated electronic records and must be readily available for FDA inspection and internal review.\n5.4 Audit trail integrity shall be verified periodically per SOP-VAL-312 (System Audit Trails and Data Integrity).\n\n6.0 BATCH RECORD REVIEW AND RELEASE PROCESS\n6.1 Batch Record Audit: The manufacturing supervisor must review the completed BMR, verifying that all entries are complete, calculations are correct, and signatures are in place. This review must be performed within the validated electronic system, and all review actions are captured in the audit trail.\n6.2 Deviation Review: All deviations, failures, and out-of-specification (OOS) investigations associated with the batch must be resolved and closed by Quality Assurance (QA) before final batch release. Closure documentation must be electronically signed and recorded in the audit trail.\n6.3 QA Certificate of Analysis (CoA): Analytical test results must meet standard release specifications. A CoA must be compiled, reviewed, and electronically signed by the Quality Control (QC) laboratory. The CoA and all supporting data must be stored in a system compliant with Section 4.0 and 5.0.\n6.4 Dual-Authorization Release: The final batch release decision requires dual-authorization. The QA Manager and a second designated QA representative must each independently review the batch documentation and execute their electronic signature to approve release. Both signatures must be dual-factor electronic signatures (e.g., user ID and password plus a biometric or token) as defined in SOP-QA-204 (Electronic Signatures and Signing Authority). The system shall record both approvals in the audit trail with date, time, and signatory identity.\n6.5 Post-Release Modifications: Any modification to a released batch record automatically invalidates the existing electronic release manifest and requires a new dual-authorization release process. The reason for modification must be documented and approved via a deviation or change control.\n\n7.0 TRAINING\nAll personnel involved in batch record review and release must complete training on this SOP and the referenced system access and electronic signature procedures. Training records shall be maintained in the learning management system.\n\n8.0 REFERENCES\n- 21 CFR Part 11: Electronic Records; Electronic Signatures\n- FDA Docket No. FDA-2026-N-8841\n- SOP-IT-101: Electronic Records and System Access Control\n- SOP-VAL-312: System Audit Trails and Data Integrity\n- SOP-QA-204: Electronic Signatures and Signing Authority\n\n9.0 REVISION HISTORY\nVersion 1: Initial release\nVersion 2: Comprehensive revision to incorporate electronic record integrity controls, audit trail requirements, encryption, session timeout, password aging, and dual-authorization release per FDA-2026-N-8841.",
"citations": [
"21 CFR Part 11.10",
"21 CFR Part 11.30",
"21 CFR Part 11.200",
"21 CFR Part 11.300",
"FDA-2026-N-8841"
],
"rationale": "The original SOP-110 lacked specific technical controls for electronic records and signatures, relying only on a dual-factor signature for release. The revised SOP incorporates mandatory system access controls (password complexity, aging, account lockout, 15-minute session timeout), encryption of records in transit (TLS 1.3), and a computer-generated, time-stamped audit trail for all actions on electronic batch records. Additionally, the release process was changed from a single QA Manager signature to a dual-authorization model requiring two independent QA approvals, aligning with the new regulation's requirement for strict dual-authorization on document releases. All changes are directly linked to 21 CFR Part 11 and the FDA-2026-N-8841 update, ensuring the batch record review and release process produces trustworthy and reliable electronic records equivalent to paper records."
}
